Compute the product of the number $5+\sqrt{3}$ and its radical conjugate.
inference:
$$(5+\sqrt{3})\times(5-\sqrt{3})$$
$$=5^2-(\sqrt{3})^2 \quad \because (a+b)(a-b)=a^2-b^2$$
$$=25-3$$
$$=22$$
Final Answer: \boxed{$22$}. I hope it is correct.
ground_truth: The radical conjugate of this number is $5-\sqrt{3},$ so the product of the two numbers is \[(5+\sqrt3)(5-\sqrt3) = 5^2 - (\sqrt3)^2 = 25 - 3 = \boxed{22}.\]
